0":"1320","before 1240":"vóór 1240","1242":"1242","1252":"1252","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","about 1276":"circa 1276","1290":"1290","Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire district, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England","Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire, England":"Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire, England","Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1240–1320":"1240–1320","1242–Male":"1242–Deceased","1260–Female":"1260–Deceased","1290–1324":"1290–1324","1205–1252":"1205–1252","1215–Female":"1215–Deceased","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","1324":"1324","1320":"1320","before 1240":"before 1240","1242":"1242","1252":"1252","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","about 1276":"about 1276","1290":"1290","Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire district, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England","Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire, England":"Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire, England","Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Halle","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Rejean, Marcel, Andre, Arianne, Armand, Camille, Fernand, Gaspard, Laurent.","German and English: variant of   Hall  .","French (also <b>Hallé</b>): topographic name from Old French <i>halle</i> ‘covered market’, from <i>halla</i> ‘covered room’."],"variants":[{"name":"Hall","meanings":["English, Scottish, Irish, German, Norwegian, and Danish: from Middle English <i>hall</i> (Old English <i>heall</i>), Middle High German <i>halle</i>, Old Norse <i>hǫll</i> all meaning ‘hall’ (a spacious residence), hence a topographic name for someone who lived in or near a hall or an occupational name for a servant employed at a hall. In some cases it may be a habitational name from any of the places called with this word, which in some parts of Germany and Austria in the Middle Ages also denoted a salt mine. Hall is one of the commonest and most widely distributed of English surnames, bearing witness to the importance of the hall as a feature of the medieval village. The English surname has been established in Ireland since the 14th century, and, according to MacLysaght, has become numerous in Ulster since the 17th century.","Swedish: ornamental or topographic name from <i>hall</i> ‘hall’ (a spacious residence), or a habitational name from a placename containing the element <i>hall</i> ‘rock’ (from Old Norse <i>hallr</i>).","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surnames 何 and 賀, see   He   1 and 2."]},{"name":"Hallee","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alain, Armand, Fernand, Henri, Napoleon, Renald, Urbain.","French Canadian (also <b>Hallée</b>): variant of <b>Hallé</b> (see   Halle   3)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Halle was born in 1240, in Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Reginald de Halle, was 35 and his mother, Agnes, was 25. He married Catherine de la Salle about 1276. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1320, in his hometown, at the age of 80."},"et":{"1240–1320":"1240–1320","1242–Male":"1242–Surnud","1260–Female":"1260–Surnud","1290–1324":"1290–1324","1205–1252":"1205–1252","1215–Female":"1215–Surnud","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","1324":"1324","1320":"1320","before 1240":"enne 1240","1242":"1242","1252":"1252","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","about 1276":"umbes 1276","1290":"1290","Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire district, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England","Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire, England":"Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire, England","Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1240–1320":"1240–1320","1242–Male":"1242–Kuollut","1260–Female":"1260–Kuollut","1290–1324":"1290–1324","1205–1252":"1205–1252","1215–Female":"1215–Kuollut","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","1324":"1324","1320":"1320","before 1240":"ennen vuotta 1240","1242":"1242","1252":"1252","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","about 1276":"noin 1276","1290":"1290","Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire district, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Wiltshir